{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3dde2278-0daa-4d5e-90a4-4779c16c41f3","content":"I don't see the project at that path, but here's how to configure it regardless.\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout, which is the standard transport for local MCP servers.\n- **`command` / `args`** — uses `dotnet run` to build and launch your project.\n- Make sure your server reads from stdin and writes to stdout (e.g., using the `ModelContextProtocol` or `Microsoft.Extensions.AI` SDK with `WithStdioServerTransport()`).\n- If you publish the server as a standalone executable instead, replace `command`/`args` with the path to the binary.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2697b910-cb06-4393-99f3-ff696287e829","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but the user said they built it. Regardless, I can still provide the correct `mcp.json` configuration for a C# MCP server using `dotnet run` with stdio transport.","outputTokens":325,"requestId":"5037:1DFA19:D9B3A5:F9A442:69F2AB3E"},"id":"cd067d2f-41b5-4065-b4e9-c13d9e225fe0","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:07:19.423Z","parentId":"bb7bde19-495d-4992-9e2c-8b250d33384b"}
